# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ballpark
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ballpark/16-inch-softball] The first set of rules was published in 1937 by the Amateur Softball Association, in the same manual as the rules for fastpitch softball.
[src:ballpark/16-inch-softball] Game play for 16-inch softball is mostly consistent with standard softball game play.
[src:ballpark/16-inch-softball] In contrast to standard, or 12-inch (30.48 cm) softball, it is played with a ball 16 inches (40.64 cm) in circumference.
[src:ballpark/16-inch-softball] It is common to see higher arched pitching, and balls/strikes are determined by where the ball lands and crosses the batter's body.
[src:ballpark/16-inch-softball] Leagues may form co-ed, all-male, or all-female teams.
[src:ballpark/16-inch-softball] Additionally, teams may choose competitive or recreational leagues.
[src:ballpark/16-inch-softball] There may be rule variations associated with the specific field or league of play.
[src:ballpark/16-inch-softball] When playing in a co-ed league, there may be other rules that relate to the male-to-female ratio of team members and batting order.
[src:ballpark/16-inch-softball] The National Softball Association (NSA) also has a published set of rules governing 16-inch softball play.
[src:ballpark/16-inch-softball] The earliest known softball game of any kind was played at the Farragut Boat Club in Chicago on Thanksgiving Day 1887.
[src:ballpark/16-inch-softball] The first softball was a wrapped up boxing glove and the bat was a broom.
[src:ballpark/16-inch-softball] Play was encouraged by a reporter, George Hancock, who had been looking on.
[src:ballpark/16-inch-softball] Harvard and Yale students played the game while waiting to hear the results of the annual Harvard-Yale football game.
[src:ballpark/16-inch-softball] Until the turn of the 20th century, ball sizes ranged from 12 to 17 inches in circumference.
[src:ballpark/16-inch-softball] The 16-inch softball was eventually adopted in Chicago, perhaps because it did not travel as far as the popular 12- or 14-inch balls.
[src:ballpark/16-inch-softball] This also may have allowed for play on smaller playgrounds or even indoors, accommodating the Chicago landscape and climate.
[src:ballpark/16-inch-softball] Another possible advantage of the 16-inch ball was that it allowed everyone to play barehanded, and gloves were a rare luxury as the Great Depression hit Chicago particularly hard.
[src:ballpark/16-inch-softball] After the first national championship held in 1933 at the Century of Progress World's Fair, the sport grew in popularity.
[src:ballpark/16-inch-softball] A professional league was formed that lasted through the 1950s.
[src:ballpark/16-inch-softball] Teams drew crowds of over 10,000 each night.
[src:ballpark/16-inch-softball] Leagues continue today but not at the same level of popularity.
[src:ballpark/16-inch-softball] There are co-ed recreational leagues, competitive leagues and even a league for Chicago Public School students.
[src:ballpark/16-inch-softball] Many local organizations host regular season play, typically weekly games, as well as their own playoff systems.
[src:ballpark/16-inch-softball] National organizations, such as the NSA, host a variety of tournaments.
[src:ballpark/16-inch-softball] By placing well in NSA tournaments, teams can qualify and compete for the 16-inch softball world series.
[src:ballpark/16-inch-softball] Because local leagues may have slight variations in rules, the NSA world series is played by its own set of world series rules.
[src:ballpark/16-inch-softball] One notable change is that Chicago area players, who typically are not allowed to wear gloves, may choose to wear gloves in world series games.
[src:ballpark/16-inch-softball] Games are played with a deBeer Clincher 16" ball and gloves are used.
[src:ballpark/16-inch-softball] In 1996 Al Maag and Tony Reibel established the 16" Softball Hall of Fame.
[src:ballpark/16-inch-softball] Since inception, the organization has held annual inductee dinners attended by over 600 guests.
[src:ballpark/16-inch-softball] There is a museum in Forest Park, Illinois, a suburb of Chicago.
[src:ballpark/16-inch-softball] 16inchsoftballhof.com The Chicago 16" Softball Hall of Fame is a registered 501(c) not-for-profit organization.
[src:ballpark/16-inch-softball] The game can be seen being played in multiple scenes in the 1986 film *About Last Night*, whose storyline was set in Chicago.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] The **1903 World Series** was the first modern World Series to be played in Major League Baseball.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] It matched the American League (AL) champion Boston Americans (now the Boston Red Sox) against the National League (NL) champion Pittsburgh Pirates in a best-of-nine series, with Boston prevailing five games to three, winning the last four.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] This was the first major professional sports championship ever won by a Boston-based team.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] The first three games were played in Boston, the next four in Allegheny (home of the Pirates), and the eighth (last) game in Boston.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] Pittsburgh pitcher Sam Leever injured his shoulder while trap shooting, so his teammate Deacon Phillippe pitched five complete games.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] Phillippe won three of his games, but it was not enough to overcome the club from the new American League.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] Boston pitchers Bill Dinneen and Cy Young led Boston to victory.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] In Game 1, Phillippe struck out ten Boston batters.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] The next day, Dinneen bettered that mark, striking out 11 Pittsburgh batters in Game 2.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] Honus Wagner, bothered by injuries, batted only 6-for-27 (.222) in the Series and committed six errors.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] The shortstop was deeply distraught by his performance.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] The following spring, Wagner (who in 1903 led the National League in batting average) refused to send his portrait to a "Hall of Fame" for batting champions.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] "I was a joke in that Boston-Pittsburgh Series.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] What does it profit a man to hammer along and make a few hits when they are not needed only to fall down when it comes to a pinch?
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] Due to overflow crowds at the Exposition Park games in Allegheny City, if a batted ball rolled under a rope in the outfield that held spectators back, a "ground-rule triple" would be scored.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] 17 ground-rule triples were hit in the four games played at the stadium.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] In the series, Boston came back from a three games to one deficit, winning the final four games to capture the title.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] Such a large comeback would not happen again until the Pirates came back to defeat the Washington Senators in the 1925 World Series, and has happened only 11 times in baseball history.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] (The Pirates themselves repeated this feat in 1979 against the Baltimore Orioles.) Much was made of the influence of Boston's "Royal Rooters", who traveled to Exposition Park and sang their theme song "Tessie" to distract the opposing players (especially Wagner).
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] Boston wound up winning three out of four games in Allegheny City.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] Pirates owner Barney Dreyfuss added his share of the gate receipts to the players' share, so the losing team's players actually finished with a larger individual share than the winning team's.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] The Series brought the new American League prestige and proved its best could beat the best of the National League, thus strengthening the demand for future World Series competitions.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] In 1901, Ban Johnson, president of the Western League, a minor league organization, formed the American League to take advantage of the National League's 1900 contraction from twelve teams to eight.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] Johnson and fellow owners raided the National League and signed away many star players, including Cy Young and Jimmy Collins.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] Johnson had a list of 46 National Leaguers he targeted for the American League; by 1902, all but one had made the jump.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] The constant raiding, however, nixed the idea of a championship between the two leagues.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] Pirates owner Barney Dreyfuss, whose team ran away with the 1902 National League pennant, was open to a postseason contest and even said he would allow the American League champion to stock its roster with all-stars.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] However, Johnson had spoken of putting a team in Pittsburgh and even attempted to raid the Pirates' roster in August 1902, which soured Dreyfuss.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] At the end of the season, however, the Pirates played a group of American League All-Stars in a four-game exhibition series, winning two games to one, with one tie.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] The leagues finally called a truce in the winter of 1902–03 and formed the National Commission to preside over organized baseball.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] The following season, the Boston Americans and Pittsburgh Pirates had secured their respective championship pennants by September.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] That August, Dreyfuss challenged the American League to an 11-game championship series.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] Encouraged by Johnson and National League President Harry Pulliam, Americans owner Henry J.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] Killilea met with Dreyfuss in Pittsburgh in September and instead agreed to a best-of-nine championship, with the first three games played in Boston, the next four in Allegheny City, and the remaining two (if necessary) in Boston.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] One significant point about this agreement was that it was an arrangement primarily between the two clubs rather than a formal arrangement between the leagues.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] In short, it was a voluntary event, a fact which would result in no Series at all for 1904.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] The formal establishment of the Series as a compulsory event started in 1905.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] The Pirates won their third straight pennant in 1903 thanks to a powerful lineup that included legendary shortstop Honus Wagner, who hit .355 and drove in 101 runs, player-manager Fred Clarke, who hit .351, and Ginger Beaumont, who hit .341 and led the league in hits and runs.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] The Pirates' pitching was weaker than it had been in previous years but boasted 24-game winner Deacon Phillippe and 25-game winner Sam Leever.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] The Americans had a strong pitching staff, led by Cy Young, who went 28–9 in 1903 and became the all-time wins leader that year.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] Bill Dinneen and Long Tom Hughes, right-handers like Young, had won 21 games and 20 games each.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] The Boston outfield, featuring Chick Stahl (.274), Buck Freeman (.287, 104 RBI) and Patsy Dougherty (.331, 101 runs scored) was considered excellent.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] Although the Pirates had dominated their league for the previous three years, they went into the series riddled with injuries and plagued by bizarre misfortunes.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] Otto Krueger, the team's only utility player, was beaned on September 19 and never fully played in the series.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] 16-game winner Ed Doheny left the team three days later, exhibiting signs of paranoia; he was committed to an insane asylum the following month.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] Leever had been battling an injury to his pitching arm (which he made worse by entering a trapshooting competition).
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] Worst of all, Wagner, who had a sore thumb throughout the season, injured his right leg in September and was never 100 percent for the postseason.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] Some sources say Boston were heavy underdogs.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] Boston bookies actually gave even odds to the teams (and only because Dreyfuss and other "sports" were alleged to have bet on Pittsburgh to bring down the odds).
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] The teams were generally thought to be evenly matched, with the Americans credited with stronger pitching and the Pirates with superior offense and fielding.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] The outcome, many believed, hinged on Wagner's health.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] The Pirates started Game 1 strong, scoring six runs in the first four innings, and held on to win the first World Series game in modern baseball history.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] They extended their lead to 7–0 on an inside-the-park home run by Jimmy Sebring in the seventh, the first home run in World Series history.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] Boston scored a few runs in the last three innings, but it was too little, too late; they ended up losing 7–3 in the first ever World Series game.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] Both Phillippe and Young threw complete games, with Phillippe striking out ten and Young fanning five, but Young also gave up twice as many hits and allowed three earned runs to Phillippe's two.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] After starting out strong in Game 1, the Pirates simply shut down offensively, eking out a mere three hits, all singles.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] Pittsburgh starter Sam Leever went 1 inning and gave up three hits and two runs, before his ailing arm forced him to leave in favor of Bucky Veil, who finished the game.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] Bill Dinneen struck out 11 and pitched a complete game for the Americans, while Patsy Dougherty hit home runs in the first and sixth innings for two of the Boston's three runs.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] The Americans' Patsy Dougherty led off the Boston scoring with an inside-the-park home run, the first time a lead-off batter did just that until Alcides Escobar of the Kansas City Royals duplicated the feat in the 2015 World Series, 112 years later.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] Dougherty's second home run was the first in World Series history to actually sail over the fence, an incredibly rare feat at the time.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] Phillippe, pitching after only a single day of rest, started Game 3 for the Pirates and didn't let them down, hurling his second complete-game victory of the Series to put Pittsburgh up two games to one.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] After two days of rest, Phillippe was ready to pitch a second straight game.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] He threw his third complete-game victory of the series against Bill Dinneen, who was making his second start of the series.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] But Phillippe's second straight win was almost not to be, as the Americans, down 5–1 in the top of the ninth, rallied to narrow the deficit to one run.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] The comeback attempt failed, as Phillippe managed to put an end to it and give the Pirates a commanding 3–1 series lead.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] Game 5 was a pitcher's duel for the first five innings, with Boston's Cy Young and Pittsburgh's Brickyard Kennedy giving up no runs.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] That changed in the top of the sixth, however, when the Americans scored a then-record six runs before being retired.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] Young, on the other hand, managed to keep his shutout intact before finally giving up a pair of runs in the bottom of the eighth.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] He went the distance and struck out four for his first World Series win.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] Game 6 was a rematch between the starters of Game 2, Boston's Dinneen and Pittsburgh's Leever.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] Leever pitched a complete game this time but so did Dinneen, who outmatched him to earn his second complete-game victory of the series.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] After losing three of the first four games of the World Series, the underdog Americans had tied the series at three games apiece.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] The fourth and final game in Allegheny saw Phillippe start his fourth game of the Series for the Pirates.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] This time, however, he did not fare as well as he did in his first three starts.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] Cy Young, in his third start of the Series, held the Pirates to three runs and put the Americans ahead for the first time as the Series moved back to Boston.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] The final game of this inaugural World Series started out as an intense pitcher's duel, scoreless until the bottom of the fourth when Hobe Ferris hit a two-run single.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] Phillippe started his fifth and final game of the series and Dinneen his fourth.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] The Red Sox would go on to be one of the most dominant teams of the early 20th century, winning four championships in six years during the 1910s decade.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] They would start their dynasty in 1912 when they won their next championship over the New York Giants in seven games.
[src:ballpark/1903-world-series] The Pirates would return to the World Series in 1909, and defeated the Detroit Tigers in seven games to win their first championship.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The **1932 Summer Olympics** (officially the **Games of the X Olympiad** and also known as **Los Angeles 1932**) were an international multi-sport event held from July 30 to August 14, 1932, in Los Angeles, California, United States.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The Games were held during the worldwide Great Depression, with some nations not traveling to Los Angeles as a result; 37 countries competed, compared to the 46 at the 1928 Games in Amsterdam, and even then-U.S.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] President Herbert Hoover did not attend the Games.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The organizing committee was led by William May Garland, a local sports enthusiast and real estate developer.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] Los Angeles will host the Summer Olympics for the third time in 2028, becoming the third city in the world—following London and Paris—to do so.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The selection of the host city for the 1932 Summer Olympics was made at the 23rd IOC Session in Rome, Italy, in 1923.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] Remarkably, the selection process consisted of a single bid, from Los Angeles's Olympic bid Committee led by William May Garland, and as there were no bids from any other city, Los Angeles was selected by default to host the 1932 Games.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] Los Angeles was awarded the games on April 9, 1923.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] William May Garland led the Organizing Committee for the Olympic Games (OCOG), officially titled the "Xth Olympiad Committee" with a staff of 70 employees.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The Games were originally heavily backed by local corporate interests and L.A. business elites.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] They were primarily underwritten by a US $1 million (equivalent to US $18.67 million in 2024) state bond act, the “California Olympic Bond Act of 1927″.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] Later approved as "Proposition 2" by CA voters with 73% of the vote in 1928.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The OCOG raised funds from various sources.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] 1,247,580 worth of ticket sales, 42.4% of venues capacity bringing in US $1.48 million (equivalent to US $27.69 million in 2024).
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The OCOG received a share of venue concessions run by a local firm at each venue bringing in sales revenue.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The OCOG charged US $2 (equivalent to US $37.35 in 2024) a day for male athletes and coaches to stay at the Olympic Village.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] Lastly, corporate sponsors like, Omega, Helms Bakery and Coca-Cola provided a revenue source.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] Most venues were rented out or leased at no cost to the OCOG.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The OCOG paid for the dredging of Alamitos Bay in Long Beach for rowing events.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] They paid for the Olympic Village, a pool for swimming events and paid for temporary stands at city parks and golf courses used.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] Including concessions, post-games equipment sales and the bond, estimates of earnings have been placed as high as US $2.7 million (equivalent to US $50.42 million in 2024).
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The OCOG did not report the financial details of the Games, although contemporary newspapers stated that the Games had made a profit of US $1 million (equivalent to US $18.67 million in 2024) at closing ceremony.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] Steckel and the four other committee members deployed 650 police officers dedicated to traffic control every day of the Games.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The Chief ordered police officers to work 12-hour days and to postpone vacations.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] 150 university students assisted the police as traffic officers.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The L.A.P.D. employed 800 duly sworn police officers.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] According to the L.A.P.D.'s official site, crime was very low during the Olympics.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] Automobiles were the primary method of transportation.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] A five-member traffic committee was organized by the OCOG with the Los Angeles Police Department (LAPD) and traffic management experts.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] Athletes were transported in sixty eight bus carriages to competition venues and the Olympic Village in Baldwin Hills.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The OCOG urged attendees to use the red car trolleys to avoid congestion at venues, the Pacific Electric trolleys were the largest rail network in the world at the turn of the century.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] Fifteen sports venues were used for the 1932 Summer Olympics.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] In order to control costs in the wake of the Great Depression, existing venues were used.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] They included two golf courses, two city parks, three public highways, and a city road.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The Swimming Stadium was the only new venue constructed for these games.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The Rose Bowl, constructed in 1921, was made into a temporary velodrome for track cycling events under the auspices of the Union Cycliste Internationale (UCI).
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum, constructed in 1923, was used as the Olympic Stadium.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The Olympic Auditorium was constructed in 1924 in preparation for Los Angeles being awarded the Games; it was modified to meet the specifications of the boxing, weightlifting, and wrestling federations.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] Long Beach Marine Stadium was created in 1925 when Alamitos Bay was dredged, then further dredged seven years later in time for the 1932 Games.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] Elysian Park, the oldest city park in Los Angeles, was founded in 1886, and has been part of the Los Angeles Police Department (LAPD) training academy since 1925.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The Riviera Country Club opened in 1926 as the Los Angeles Athletic Club Golf Course and was renamed Riviera by the time of the 1932 Games.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] Equestrian events were held in various locations.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The equestrian cross country route was designed by U.S.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] Cavalry officers John Burke Barry and Sloan Doak, members of the IFE and former Olympians.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] It was known for being brutally difficult and bisecting multiple rural highways, starting from the Riviera Country Club, thru Santa Monica, West Los Angeles, the Olympic Village and ending at Sunset Fields Gold Club.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] Named the "Westchester course", although the course did not enter the modern-day neighborhood boundaries of Westchester.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] Dressage was held at the Riviera Country Club and show jumping at the Coliseum.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The Swimming Stadium, constructed adjacent to the Coliseum in 1932, was intended to be a temporary structure.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] LA introduced the first Olympic Village, providing housing for male athletes.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The accommodations provided in Los Angeles Baldwin Hills neighborhood is considered to be the first official modern Olympic Village, with a capacity of 2,000 people and located to the west of the city.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] Consisting of a group of buildings with rooms to lodge athletes (men only), as well as providing a place to eat and train, it serves as the model for today's Olympic Villages.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] It also provided certain community services for the first time, including a hospital, a fire station, and a post office.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The Art competitions at the 1932 Summer Olympics awarded medals for works inspired by sport-related themes in five categories: architecture, literature, music, painting, and sculpture.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] American pianist Walter Bradley-Keeler composed "Hymne Olympique", an anthem written specifically for the Xth Olympiad.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The IOC would make it the official anthem before the current Olympic anthem was created in 1958.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] Opening ceremony tickets were sold for US $3 (equivalent to US $56.02 in 2024) each.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] Events tickets ranged between US $1 (equivalent to US $18.67 in 2024) to US $3 (equivalent to US $56.02 in 2024) per individual event.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] A US $22 (equivalent to US $410.8 in 2024) pass was available to enter the Coliseum for all events.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] Children's tickets were available for US $0.5 (equivalent to US $9.34 in 2024) cents for all events.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The emblem was created by Harry Muir Kurtzworth and the OCOG's in-house art department.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] It featured the coat of arms of the United States holding the Olympic rings, along with the Olympic motto Citius, Altius, Fortius (Faster, Higher, Stronger) and a laurel branch.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The main colors used were red, white and blue, representing the flag of the United States.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] For the first time, colors were assigned to each sport discipline.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] Colors were used for programs, badges, athlete identifications and event venue branding.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] Although not a sport discipline, the Art Festival was assigned "Mocha Brown" as the designated color.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] An Olympic mascot, Scottish Terrier Smoky, was featured for the first time in history, albeit unofficially.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The games introduced consumer culture to the Olympics, relying on local corporate sponsorships and partnerships with the Hollywood film industry of the time.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] Iconic brands like Coca-Cola expanded their early Olympic presence in 1932 serving as the "official soft drink" of the Games.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] Local baked goods maker Helms Bakery provided baked food items, including Helms Olympic Bread, the "official baker"." Omega SA also debuted as the "official timekeeper" of the games; they provided one watchmaker and thirty chronographs for officials.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The Jeffries Printing Co. was the official printing supplier for the games.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] A total of 37 nations were represented at the 1932 Games.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] Colombia made its first appearance at the Olympic Games, and the Republic of China competed for the first time after its failed appearance at the 1924 Games.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] For the first time, all discipline events were held within 16 days, 3 weekends within the opening and closing ceremonies.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] A pattern that has been kept ever since.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] No previous Summer Olympics had lasted less than 79 days.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] LAOOC organized 117 events in 14 sports across 20 disciplines.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] As none of the equestrian teams managed to have three riders finish the Team jumping event course on the 14th day of August, no team medal was awarded.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The ceremony included a 300-person orchestra, and a choir of 1,200 singers.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] Organizing committee President William May Garland provided opening remarks of welcome on behaf of California and the City of Los Angeles before introducing Vice President Curtis to officially open the games.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The ceremony lasted two hours, 2,000 athletes, coaches, and officials from 37 nations participated.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] Also, 800 journalists, including 200 from abroad were issued press passes.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The closing ceremony was celebrated on Sunday, August 14, 1932, also at the Coliseum.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The coliseum hosted Equestrian (Prix des Nations) Jumping and dressage events at 2:30 PM.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] After the conclusion of the event, the crowd of just under 100,000 remained to witness the closure of the games.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The games orchestra was present, they commenced the start of the parade of nations at sunset.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] Placards with country names with their respected flag entered the Coliseum.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] Once complete, IOC president Billet-Latour proclaimed the "youth of the world to assemble in Berlin", in four years time.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The Olympic flag was lowered and presented to Major George van Rossem, President of the Dutch Olympic committee, he then forwarded the flag to the IOC president who then gave it to Los Angeles Mayor Porter, to safe keep until the next Olympic Games in Berlin.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] Trumpets, fanfare and cannons boomed as the nations flags exited the stadium.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The orchestra played "Aloha ʻOe", a farewell song as the remaining flag bearer exited.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The orchestra then played "taps", the olympic flame was extinguished ending the ceremony and the games.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] 117 events in 20 disciplines, comprising 14 sports, were part of the Olympic program in 1932.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] Football was introduced in Paris 1900 Games.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] Following Jules Rimet's proposal in 1929 to initiate a professional World Championship tournament of football, the sport was then dropped from the 1932 Games by FIFA in an attempt to promote the new World Cup tournament of 1930.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] Football returned for the 1936 Games in Berlin.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] In one of two Equestrian jumping events (team competitions) no medals were awarded.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1932 Games.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] Before the 1932 Games, all the medals were awarded at the closing ceremony, with the athletes wearing evening dress for the occasion.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The presenting dignitary was stationary while the athletes filed past to receive their medals.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The presentation of the medals and awards varied significantly until the 1932 Summer Olympics.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] Los Angeles introduced protocol that has now become standard.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] In Los Angeles, athletes were honored by introducing the first true victory podium, the raising of the medalists' national flags, and the playing of the winner's national anthem.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] These ceremonies were held immediately following events at the Memorial Coliseum.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] No television rights were offered as TV technology was not available until 1936.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] Live, real-time radio broadcasts of the Games were severely restricted.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The OCOG attempted to sell the live radio feed to NBC Radio Network and CBS News Radio for US $100,000 (equivalent to US $1.87 million in 2024).
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] They refused to pay the fee, relying instead on reports and summaries by local newspaper affiliates.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] The primary visual medium for the 1932 Games were theater newsreels.
[src:ballpark/1932-summer-olympics] Spectators globally could watch highlights of events in movie theaters after the fact.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Montreal was awarded the rights to the 1976 Games at the 69th IOC Session in Amsterdam on May 12, 1970, over the bids of Moscow and Los Angeles.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] It is the only Summer Olympic Games to be held in Canada.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Toronto hosted the 1976 Summer Paralympics the same year as the Montreal Olympics, also the only Summer Paralympics to be held in Canada.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Calgary and Vancouver later hosted the Winter Olympic Games in 1988 and 2010, respectively.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] This was the first of two consecutive Olympic games held in North America, followed by the 1980 Winter Olympics in Lake Placid.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] The Soviet Union won the most gold and overall medals, with the Eastern Bloc having seven countries in the top 10 of the medal table.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] The vote occurred at the 69th IOC Session in Amsterdam, Netherlands on May 12, 1970.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] While Los Angeles and Moscow were viewed as the favourites, given that they represented the world's two main powers, many of the smaller and neutral countries supported Montreal as an underdog and as a relatively neutral site for the Games.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Los Angeles was eliminated after the first round, and Montreal won over Moscow in the second round.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Moscow and Los Angeles would go on to host the next two Summer Games, 1980 and 1984 Summer Olympics, respectively, which were also marked by political boycotts (for instance, the U.S.-led boycott of the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan in 1979).
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] One blank vote was cast in the second and final round.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] The Soviet state media accused the IOC of political corruption following the vote, accusing them of facilitating the Soviet Union's loss.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Toronto had made its third attempt for the Olympics, as did Hamilton.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Still, they failed to win the support of the Canadian Olympic Committee, which selected Montreal instead.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Another candidate was the Italian city of Florence, which announced that it would withdraw from contention two months before the vote.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Robert Bourassa, then the Premier of Quebec, asked Prime Minister Pierre Trudeau to advise Canada's monarch Elizabeth II to attend the opening of the games.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] However, Bourassa later became unsettled about how unpopular the move might be with sovereigntists in the province, annoying Trudeau, who had already made arrangements.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] René Lévesque, the leader of the Parti Québécois at the time, sent his own letter to Buckingham Palace, asking the Queen to refuse her prime minister's request, but she did not oblige Lévesque as he was out of his jurisdiction in offering advice to the Sovereign.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] In 1976, Trudeau, succumbing to pressure from the People's Republic of China, issued an order barring Taiwan from participating as China in the 1976 Montreal Olympics, although it was technically a matter for the IOC.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] His action strained relations with the United States – from President Ford to future President Carter and the press.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Trudeau's action was widely condemned as having brought shame on Canada by succumbing to political pressure to keep the Taiwanese delegation from competing under its name.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] The mascot was a beaver named Amik, whose name was chosen after a national competition.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] The *Oxford Olympics Study* estimates the outturn cost of the Montreal 1976 Summer Olympics at US$6.1 billion in 2015 dollars and cost overrun at 720% in real terms.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] *Indirect* capital costs are not included, such as those for road, rail, or airport infrastructure, or for hotel upgrades or other business investment incurred in preparation for the Games but not directly related to staging the Games.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] The cost overrun for Montreal 1976 is the highest cost overrun on record for any Olympics.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] The cost and cost overrun for Montreal 1976 compares with costs of US$4.6 billion and a cost overrun of 51% for Rio de Janeiro in 2016 and $15 billion and 76% for London in 2012.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] The average cost for the Summer Games from 1960 to 2016 was $5.2 billion in 2015 dollars, and the average cost overrun was 176%.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] French architect Roger Taillibert, who designed the Olympic stadium, recounted in his 2000 book *Notre Cher Stade Olympique* that he and Mayor Drapeau tried hard to buy off Desjardins, even taking him to a lunch at the exclusive Ritz-Carlton hotel in a vain attempt to end the "delays".
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] He suggests that Quebec Premier Robert Bourassa ultimately made a secret deal to buy off Desjardins, which allowed work to proceed.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Taillibert wrote in *Notre Cher Stade Olympique* "If the Olympic Games took place, it was thanks to Dede Desjardins.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] What irony!" The delays and scandals caused Quebec premier Robert Bourassa to take over the preparations of the games in November 1975.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] The Vélodrome de Montréal, which was scheduled for opening in 1974, was finally completed in June 1976, a month before the opening ceremony.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony of the 1976 Summer Olympic Games was held at the incomplete Olympic Stadium in Montreal, Quebec on Saturday afternoon, July 17, 1976, in front of an audience of some 73,000 in the stadium and an estimated half billion watching on television.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Following an air show by the Canadian Forces Air Command's Snowbirds aerobatic flight demonstration squadron in the sunny skies above the stadium, the ceremony officially began at 3:00 pm with a trumpet fanfare and the arrival of Elizabeth II, as Queen of Canada.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] The Queen entered the Royal Box with her consort, Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh, and her son, Prince Andrew.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] (Her daughter, Princess Anne, was competing as a member of Great Britain's equestrian team.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] The parade of athletes began moments later with the arrival of the Greek team, and concluded with the entrance of the Canadian team.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] All other teams entered the stadium according to French alphabetical order (as the host city's main language).
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] The ceremony was marked by the adorning of Israel's flag with a black mourning ribbon, in memory of the eleven athletes and coaches killed by Palestinian terrorists at the previous Summer Olympic Games in Munich four years earlier.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Although most would eventually boycott the Games in the days to follow, a number of African delegations did march in the parade.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Much of the music performed for the parade was arranged by Victor Vogel and was inspired by late Quebecois composer André Mathieu.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Immediately following the parade, a troupe of 80 female dancers dressed in white (representing the 80th anniversary of the revival of the Olympic Games) performed a brief dance in the outline of the Olympic rings.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Following that came the official speeches, first by Roger Rousseau, head of the Montreal Olympic organizing committee, and Lord Killanin.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Her Majesty was then invited to proclaim the Games open, which she did, first in French, then in English.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Accompanied by the Olympic Hymn, the Olympic flag was carried into the stadium and hoisted at the west end of the stadium.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] The flag was carried by eight men and hoisted by four women, representing the ten provinces and two territories (at the time) of Canada.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] As the flag was hoisted, an all-male choir performed an a cappella version of the Olympic Hymn.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Once the flag was hosted, a troupe of Bavarian dancers representing Munich, host of the previous Summer Olympics, entered the stadium with the Antwerp flag.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Following a brief dance, that flag was then passed from the Mayor of Munich to the IOC President and then to the Mayor of Montreal.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Next came a presentation of traditional Québécois folk dancers.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] The two troupes merged in dance together to the strains of "Vive le Compagnie" and exited the stadium with the Antwerp Flag, which would be displayed at Montreal City Hall until the opening of the 1980 Summer Olympics in Moscow.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Three cannons were then fired, as the 80-member troupe of female dancers unfolded special crates that released doves and ribbons in the five Olympic colours.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Another trumpet fanfare announced the arrival of the Olympic Flame.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] The torch was carried by 15-year-olds Stéphane Préfontaine and Sandra Henderson, chosen as representatives of the unity within Canada's linguistic heritage.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] This would also be the first time two people would light the Olympic flame.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] The duo would make a lap of the stadium and then climbed a staircase on a special dais at the centre of the stadium to set the Olympic flame alight in a temporary white aluminum cauldron.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] The flame was later transported to a more permanent cauldron just outside the running track to burn throughout the duration of the Games.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] A choir then performed the Olympic Cantata as onlookers admired the Olympic flame.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] The "Youth of Canada" took to the track to perform a colourful choreographed segment with flags, ribbons and a variety of rhythmic gymnast performers.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] The flag bearers of each team then circled around the speaker's dais as Pierre St-Jean recited the Athletes' Oath and Maurice Forget recited the Judges' Oath, in English and in French, with right hands over their hearts and Canadian flags clutched in their left.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Finally, a choral performance of "O Canada" in both French and English marked the close of the opening ceremony, as the announcers concluded with a declaration of the Games motto: 'Vive les Jeux de Montreal!
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] The Montreal ceremony would be the last of its kind in Summer Games, as future Olympic ceremonies, beginning with the new Olympic Charter were reinforced before the 1980 Summer Olympics, would become more focused on the host country's culture.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Because of the Munich massacre, security at these games was visible.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] The extensive security measures included the requirement for all workers to hold a valid accreditation.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Surveillance of acoustics was installed in the Olympic Village where athletes were accommodated.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Furthermore, a systematic installation of closed-circuit television (CCTV) was attempted for the first time in the history of the Olympic games.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] There was a desire by the IOC's program commission to reduce the number of competitors and a number of recommendations were put to the IOC's executive board on February 23, 1973, which were all accepted.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Rowing was the only sport where the number of competitors was increased, and women were admitted for the first time in Olympic history.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Four nations made their first Summer Olympic appearance in Montreal: Andorra (which had its overall Olympic debut a few months before in Innsbruck Winter Olympics), Antigua and Barbuda (as *Antigua*), Cayman Islands, and Papua New Guinea.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Numbers in parentheses indicate the number of athletes from each nation that competed at the Games.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1976 Games.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Canada placed 27th with only 11 medals in total, none of them being gold.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Canada remains the only host nation of a Summer Olympics to fail to win at least one gold medal.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] It also did not win any gold medals at the 1988 Winter Olympics in Calgary.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] However, Canada went on to win the most gold medals at the 2010 Winter Olympics in Vancouver.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] The Games were dominated by the Soviet Bloc, with the USSR and its satellites occupying seven out of top ten places in the medal standings.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Twenty-nine countries boycotted the Games due to the refusal of the IOC to ban New Zealand, after the New Zealand national rugby union team had toured South Africa earlier in 1976.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] The boycott was led by Congolese official Jean-Claude Ganga.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Some of the boycotting nations (including Morocco, Cameroon and Egypt) had already participated, however, and withdrew after the first few days.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Senegal and Ivory Coast were the only African countries that competed throughout the duration of the Games.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Elsewhere, Afghanistan, Albania, Burma, Iraq, Guyana, Sri Lanka and Syria also opted to join the Congolese-led boycott.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] South Africa had been banned from the Olympics since 1964 due to its apartheid policies.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Other countries, such as El Salvador and Zaire, did not participate in Montreal for purely economic reasons.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] An unrelated boycott of the Montreal Games was the main issue between the Republic of China (ROC) and the People's Republic of China (PRC).
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] The ROC team withdrew from the games when Canada's Liberal government under Pierre Trudeau told it that the name "Republic of China" was not permissible at the Games because Canada had officially recognized the PRC in 1970.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Canada attempted a compromise by allowing the ROC the continued use of its national flag and anthem in the Montreal Olympic activities; the ROC refused.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] In 1979 the IOC established in the Nagoya Resolution that the PRC agreed to participate in IOC activities if the Republic of China was referred to as "Chinese Taipei".
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Another boycott would occur before the ROC would accept the provisions of the 1979 resolution.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Researchers from Germany in 2013 reported that West Germany had a state-sponsored doping program, and speculated it was in response to doping in East Germany which had existed for decades.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] ABC Sports paid US$25-million for television broadcast rights in the United States, and produced 76.5 hours of coverage.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] CBC Sports budgeted less than CAD$2-million and produced 169 hours of coverage, compared to 14 hours of programming at the 1972 Summer Olympics.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] The network expanded its coverage in 1976, when convinced there would be increased media interest from Canadians.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] When the network was criticized for spending taxpayer dollars, executive producer Bob Moir toured the country to explain the project and boasted that, "the biggest team in Montreal will be the CBC team...
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] It will be bigger than the Canadian Olympic team".
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] CBC Sports had 245 people on its crew, and aired from 9 am until 11 pm daily, taking breaks only for newscasts.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Ted Reynolds and Lloyd Robertson co-hosted coverage of the opening ceremonies.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] In 1976, CBC Sports began its practice of talking live with athletes immediately after events, and built a studio for the interviews.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] CBC broadcasters were given information kits on the athletes, prepared by Jack Sullivan, the former sports editor of The Canadian Press.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] The legacy of the Montreal Olympics is complex.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Many citizens regard the Olympiad as a financial disaster for the city as it faced debts for 30 years after the Games had finished.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] The retractable roof of the Olympic Stadium never properly worked and on several occasions has torn, prompting the stadium to be closed for extended periods of time for repairs.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] The failure of the Montreal Expos baseball club is largely blamed on the failure of the Olympic Stadium to transition into an effective and popular venue for the club – given the massive capacity of the stadium, it often looked unimpressive even with regular crowds in excess of 20,000 spectators.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] The Quebec provincial government took over construction when it became evident in 1975 that work had fallen far behind schedule.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Work was still ongoing just weeks before the opening date, and the tower was not built.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Mayor Jean Drapeau had confidently predicted in 1970 that "the Olympics can no more have a deficit than a man can have a baby", but the debt racked up to a billion dollars that the Quebec government mandated the city pay in full.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] This would prompt cartoonist Aislin to draw a pregnant Drapeau on the telephone saying, "Allo, Morgentaler?" in reference to a Montreal abortion provider.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] The Olympic Stadium was designed by French architect Roger Taillibert.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] It is often nicknamed "The Big O" as a reference to both its name and to the doughnut-shape of the permanent component of the stadium's roof, though "The Big Owe" has been used to reference the astronomical cost of the stadium and the 1976 Olympics as a whole.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] It has never had an effective retractable roof, and the tower (called the Montreal Tower) was completed only eleven years after the Olympic Games, in 1987.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] In December 2006 the stadium's costs were finally paid in full.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] The total expenditure (including repairs, renovations, construction, interest, and inflation) amounted to C$1.61 billion.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Today the stadium lacks a permanent tenant, as the Montreal Alouettes and Montreal Expos have moved, though it does host some individual games of the Alouettes as well as CF Montréal (formerly the Montreal Impact).
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] One of the streets surrounding the Olympic Stadium was renamed to honour Pierre de Coubertin, the founder of the Olympics.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] The boycott by African nations over the inclusion of New Zealand, whose rugby team had played in South Africa that year, was a contributing factor in the massive protests and civil disobedience that occurred during the 1981 Springbok Tour of New Zealand.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Official sporting contacts between South Africa and New Zealand did not occur again until after the fall of apartheid.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] Australia's failure to win a gold medal led the country to create the Australian Institute of Sport.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] In 2016, the 40th anniversary celebrations were held.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] In conjunction with the celebrations, the 2016 Quebec Games were held.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] The games were the subject of *Games of the XXI Olympiad (Jeux de la XXIe olympiade)*, a 1977 documentary film by Jean Beaudin, Marcel Carrière, Georges Dufaux and Jean-Claude Labrecque.
[src:ballpark/1976-summer-olympics] The 1976 games were also an inspiration for Australian band Black Cab's double album of 2014 entitled *Games of the XXI Olympiad*.
[src:ballpark/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] The **1993 Major League Baseball expansion** resulted in Major League Baseball (MLB) adding two expansion teams to the National League (NL) for the 1993 season: the Colorado Rockies and the Florida Marlins (now known as the Miami Marlins).
[src:ballpark/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Talks of expansion began on August 8, 1985, when the players and the owners agreed to a new collective bargaining agreement (CBA).
[src:ballpark/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] The basic agreement allowed the National League to expand by two members to match the American League, which had done so in 1977.
[src:ballpark/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Details of expansion were finalized in the 1990 CBA.
[src:ballpark/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Ten cities were considered serious candidates for the two spots: Buffalo, Charlotte, Denver, Miami, Nashville, Orlando, Phoenix, Sacramento, Tampa Bay, and Washington.
[src:ballpark/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Petersburg and Pilot Field in Buffalo were built specifically to lure an existing or expansion MLB franchise.
[src:ballpark/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] The National League expansion committee consisted of Pittsburgh Pirates Chairman Doug Danfort, New York Mets president Fred Wilpon and Houston Astros owner John McMullen.
[src:ballpark/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] On December 18, 1990, the committee eliminated Charlotte, Nashville, Phoenix and Sacramento from consideration to cut the list down to six finalists.
[src:ballpark/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] With three sites from Florida remaining in contention it became apparent that one would win out while the other spot would go to a non-Florida team.
[src:ballpark/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] After previous failed attempts to bring Major League Baseball to the state of Colorado (most notably the Pittsburgh Pirates nearly relocating to Denver following the Pittsburgh drug trials in 1985), by the late 1980s a team seemed to be a possibility in Denver.
[src:ballpark/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Eugene Orza, associate general counsel of the Major League Baseball Players Association, stated that he expected Denver would receive one of the expansion franchises.
[src:ballpark/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Colorado Baseball Commission, led by banking executive Larry Varnell, was successful in getting Denver voters to approve a 0.1% sales tax to help finance a new baseball stadium.
[src:ballpark/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Also, an advisory committee was formed in 1990 by then-Governor of Colorado Roy Romer to recruit an ownership group.
[src:ballpark/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] The group selected was led by John Antonucci, an Ohio beverage distributor, and Michael I.
[src:ballpark/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Monus, the head of the Phar-Mor drugstore chain.
[src:ballpark/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Local and regional companies—such as Erie Lake, Hensel Phelps Construction, KOA Radio, and the *Rocky Mountain News*—rounded out the group.
[src:ballpark/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Denver group chose to call their franchise the Colorado Rockies, the same name used as the National Hockey League franchise that played in Denver from 1976 to 1982.
[src:ballpark/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Senator Connie Mack III from Florida, the grandson of baseball great Connie Mack and a member of the Senate Task Force on Major League Baseball, pushed Baseball Commissioner Fay Vincent to expand to Florida.
[src:ballpark/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] On March 7, 1990, Wayne Huizenga, CEO of Blockbuster Entertainment Corporation, announced he had purchased 15% of the NFL's Miami Dolphins and 50% of the Dolphins' home, Joe Robbie Stadium, for an estimated $30 million.
[src:ballpark/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Huizenga stated his intention to aggressively pursue an expansion franchise.
[src:ballpark/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] MLB had announced a few months earlier that it intended to add two new teams to the National League.
[src:ballpark/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] It was a foregone conclusion that one of them would be placed in Florida; the only question was whether Huizenga would beat out competing groups from Orlando and Tampa Bay.
[src:ballpark/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Orlando fielded a very spirited campaign bolstered by its family-oriented tourism industry.
[src:ballpark/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Tampa Bay already had a baseball park — the Florida Suncoast Dome in St.
[src:ballpark/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] On June 10, 1990, Huizenga was awarded an expansion franchise in the National League (NL) for a $95 million expansion fee and the team began operations in 1993 as the Florida Marlins.
[src:ballpark/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] In June 1991, the expansion committee accepted the bids of the Miami and Denver groups to debut in 1993.
[src:ballpark/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Expansion was approved unanimously by all teams in July 1991.
[src:ballpark/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] An expansion draft to stock both franchises was set for November 1992.
[src:ballpark/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Though previous expansions allowed the drafting of players from the same league only, Vincent declared that the American League would receive $42 million of the National League's $190 million in expansion revenue so that the AL would provide players in the National League expansion draft.
[src:ballpark/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] In an attempt to win support in the American League and balance the vote, Vincent decreed that the AL owners were entitled to 22% of the $190 million take.
[src:ballpark/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] This decision marked the first time in expansion history that leagues were required to share expansion revenue or provide players for another league's expansion draft.
[src:ballpark/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] Vincent said the owners expanded to raise money to pay their collusion debt.
[src:ballpark/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Tampa Bay Baseball Group sued MLB for allegedly reneging on an agreement to grant an expansion team to Tampa.
[src:ballpark/1993-major-league-baseball-expansion] The suit was settled in 2003, five years after Tampa's major league team, the Devil Rays (now simply the Rays), began play in the American League.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The **1996 Summer Olympics** (officially the **Games of the XXVI Olympiad**, also known as **Atlanta 1996** and commonly referred to as the **Centennial Olympic Games**) were an international multi-sport event held from July 19 to August 4, 1996, in Atlanta, Georgia, United States.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] These were the fourth Summer Olympics to be hosted by the United States, making it the first country to have three different cities host the Summer Olympics.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] It also marked the 100th anniversary of the 1896 Summer Olympics in Athens, the inaugural edition of the modern Olympic Games.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] These were also the first Summer Olympics to be held in a different year than the Winter Olympics since the Winter Olympics commenced in 1924, as part of a new IOC practice implemented in 1994 to hold the Summer and Winter Games in alternating, even-numbered years.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The 1996 Games were the first of the two consecutive Summer Olympics to be held in a predominantly English-speaking country, preceding the 2000 Summer Olympics in Sydney, Australia.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] These were also the last Summer Olympics to be held in North America until 2028, when Los Angeles will host the games for the third time.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] A total of 24 countries made their Summer Olympic debuts in Atlanta, including 11 former Soviet republics participating for the first time as independent nations.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] With a total of 101 medals, the United States topped both the gold and overall medal count for the first time since 1984 (and for the first time since 1968 in a non-boycotted Summer Olympics), also winning the most gold (44) and silver (32) medals out of all the participating nations.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The Games were marred by violence on July 27, 1996, when a pipe bomb was detonated at Centennial Olympic Park (which had been built to serve as a public focal point for the festivities), killing two and injuring 111.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Years later, Eric Rudolph confessed to the bombing and a series of related terrorist attacks, and was sentenced to life in prison.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Nonetheless, the 1996 Olympics turned a profit, helped by record revenue from sponsorship deals and broadcast rights, and a reliance on private funding, among other factors.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] There were 8.3 million tickets sold for events at this Olympics, a record broken only in 2024.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] There was some criticism of the perceived over-commercialization of the Games, with other issues raised by European officials, such as the availability of food and transport.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Atlanta was selected on September 18, 1990, in Tokyo, Japan, over Athens, Belgrade, Manchester, Melbourne, and Toronto at the 96th IOC Session.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The city entered the competition as a dark horse, being up against stiff competition.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The US media also criticized Atlanta as a second-tier city and complained of Georgia's Confederate history.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] However, the IOC Evaluation Commission ranked Atlanta's infrastructure and facilities the highest, while IOC members said that it could guarantee large television revenues similar to the success of the 1984 Summer Olympics in Los Angeles, the most recent Olympics in the United States.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Additionally, former US ambassador to the UN and Atlanta mayor Andrew Young touted Atlanta's civil rights history and reputation for racial harmony.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Young also wanted to showcase a reformed American South.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The strong economy of Atlanta and improved race relations in the South helped to impress the IOC officials.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Coca-Cola, a long-standing partner of the Olympics, was also a strong advocate to bring the Games to its hometown.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games (ACOG) also proposed a substantial revenue-sharing with the IOC, USOC, and other NOCs.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] This would be Toronto's fourth failed attempt since 1960 (tried in 1960, 1964, and 1976, but was defeated by Rome, Tokyo and Montreal).
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Greece, the home of the ancient and first modern Olympics, was considered by many observers the "natural choice" for the Centennial Games, due to its "divine right" in history.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Athens bid chairman Spyros Metaxas gave repeated warnings to the IOC and demanded to give them the games to mark the centennial, saying "You don't hold a 100th birthday in someone else's home.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] However, the Athens bid was described as "arrogant and poorly prepared," being regarded as "not being up to the task of coping with the modern and risk-prone extravaganza" of the current Games.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The total cost of the 1996 Summer Olympics was estimated to be around US$1.7 billion.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] In total, the Games turned a profit of $19 million.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The cost for Atlanta 1996 compares with costs of $4.6 billion for Rio 2016, $40–44 billion for Beijing 2008, and $51 billion for Sochi 2014 Winter Olympics (the most expensive Olympic Games without differentiating between summer and winter in history).
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The average cost for the Summer Games since 1960 is $5.2 billion.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Using the 1984 Summer Olympics financing model, this edition was organized 100% privately without any cent of public money.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Beijing 2008 and Sochi 2014 were financed entirely by the governments of their respective countries.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] ACOG budgeted $32.7 million for Atlanta Police Department and Georgia Department of Public Safety services during the games. $70 million in funding came from the U.S. federal government for additional services, including 500 additional federal agents.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Transportation relied heavily on an expanded MARTA rail and 3,000 additional buses borrowed from nationwide transit agencies.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Ticketed events came with free public transportation.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Shuttles were provided for VIPs, athletes and olympic officials.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] These shuttles connected remote Park 'N Ride lots, central terminals, and specific competition venues.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The city implemented new High-Occupancy Vehicle lanes on I-75 and I-85 highways and coordinated traffic from a centralized Traffic Management Center to handle the daily crowds that often exceeded 500,000 people.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The games were challenged by driver shortages, route navigation errors, and logistical delays.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Events of the 1996 Games were held in a completely decentralized way using mostly existing facilities that were not built for the Games.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Most of the events were held in the so-called Olympic Ring, a 3 mi (4.8 km) circle from the center of Atlanta.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Others were held at Stone Mountain, about 20 miles (32 km) outside of the city.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] In many cases, it was decided to remove events from the Atlanta Metropolitan Region to save money, while in others the calendar was a difficulty, as was the case with association football (soccer) which ended up having its host cities spread across the Southeastern United States region.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] During early planning stages in 1992, Payne and the ACOG wanted a golf event to be held at Augusta National Golf Club.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Initially, Augusta agreed, but protests from civil rights leaders and politicians against the club's strict admission policies led to the collapse of the idea.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The Olympic Arts Festival offered 200 ticketed events, including more than 20 exhibitions in local institutions, museums, and gallery spaces.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] More than 3,000 artists participated during the two weeks of the Games.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] There were numerous free events including a daily series of music at Centennial Olympic Park, called "Southern Crossroads".
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] In 1994, African-American artist Kevin Cole was commissioned to create the Coca-Cola Centennial Olympic Wall, and the 15-story mural took two years to complete.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The Olympiad's official theme, "Summon the Heroes", was written by John Williams, making it the third Olympiad at that point for which he had composed (official composer in 1984, NBC's coverage composer in 1988).
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony featured Céline Dion singing "The Power of the Dream", the theme song of the 1996 Olympics.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The closing ceremony featured Gloria Estefan singing "Reach", the official theme song of the 1996 Olympics.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The torch relay was run from April 27 to July 19, leading up to the Games in Atlanta.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The route covered 26,875 kilometers (16,699 mi) across the United States.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The relay involved over 12,000 torchbearers, including Muhammad Ali, who was chosen to ignite the flame at the opening ceremony.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] 8.32 million tickets were sold, a record recently broken by Paris 2024.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Ticket sales brought in $420 million for the ACOG, 1/4 of its operating budget.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The "Look of the Games" design for Atlanta 1996 was named "Quilt of Leaves".
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The graphic identity featured a quilting leaf pattern.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Representing a city coming together—with laurel leaves.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The "Quilt of Leaves" theme appeared across official venues, signage, tickets, credentials, and even physically minted into the back of the Atlanta 1996 Olympic Medals.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The logo was designed by Landor Associates, it featured the Olympic flame and stars in five vibrant colors above the number 100.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The base resembled a classical Greek column to celebrate the centennial of the modern Olympic Games.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The main backdrop color was: *Georgia forest green*.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] It represented green laurels branches worn by winners in ancient Greece as well as Atlanta being nicknamed "city of trees".
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The colors palette featured *khaki gold*, *tomato orange*, *magenta*, *blue* and *purple*.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Atlanta's Olympic slogan "Come Celebrate Our Dream" was written by Jack Arogeti, a managing director at McCann-Erickson in Atlanta at the time.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The slogan was selected from more than 5,000 submitted by the public to the Atlanta Convention and Visitors Bureau.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Izzy was an abstract, amorphous tech-generated blue fantasy figure character wearing white gloves and red shoes.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] In contrast to the standing tradition of mascots of national or regional significance to the city hosting.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Created by John Ryan, an Atlanta animator from the DESIGNefx firm.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] A video game featuring the Games' mascot, *Izzy's Quest for the Olympic Rings*, was also released.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The 1996 Summer Olympics relied heavily on commercial sponsorship, 111 total domestic corporate partners.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The Atlanta-based Coca-Cola Company was the exclusive provider of soft drinks at Olympics venues, and built an attraction known as Coca-Cola Olympic City for the Games.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] As part of a sponsorship agreement with Columbia TriStar Television, the syndicated game shows *Jeopardy!* and *Wheel of Fortune* both produced episodes with Olympics tie-ins (including branded memorabilia and contests) for broadcast between April and July 1996.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] These included a *Jeopardy!* international tournament, and three weeks of *Wheel of Fortune* episodes filmed on-location at Atlanta's Fox Theatre.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The Atlanta organizing committee threatened legal actions against advertisers whose marketing implied an official association with the Games.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Several non-sponsors set up marketing activities in areas near venues, such as Samsung (competing with Motorola), which ambushed the Games with its "96 Expo".
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The city of Atlanta had also licensed street vendors to sell products from competitors to Olympic sponsors.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Nike also opened a pop-up store known as the Nike Center near the Athletes' Village, which distributed Nike-branded flags to visitors (presumably to be used at events).
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] IOC marketing director Michael Payne expressed concern for the campaign, believing that athletes could perceive them as being an insult to their accomplishments.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Payne and the United States Olympic Committee's marketing director, John Krimsky, met with Howard Slusher, a subordinate of Nike co-founder Phil Knight.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Faced with these threats, Nike agreed to retract most of its negative advertising and public relations stunts.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] A total of 197 nations, all of the then-existing and recognized National Olympic Committees, were represented at the 1996 Games, and the combined total of athletes was about 10,318.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Twenty-four countries made their Olympic debut this year, including eleven of the ex-Soviet countries that competed as part of the Unified Team in 1992.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Russia participated in the Summer Olympics separately from the other countries of the former Soviet Union for the first time since 1912 (when it was the Russian Empire).
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Russia had been a member of the Unified Team at the 1992 Summer Olympics together with 11 post-Soviet states.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The Federal Republic of Yugoslavia competed as *Yugoslavia*.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] After missing the 1992 Summer Games Afghanistan and Cambodia returned to send delegations to Atlanta.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The 14 countries making their Olympic debut were: Azerbaijan, Burundi, Cape Verde, Comoros, Dominica, Guinea-Bissau, Macedonia, Nauru, Palestinian Authority, Saint Kitts and Nevis, Saint Lucia, São Tomé and Príncipe, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The ten countries making their Summer Olympic debut (after competing at the 1994 Winter Olympics in Lillehammer) were: Armenia, Belarus, Czech Republic, Georgia, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Moldova, Slovakia, Ukraine and Uzbekistan.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The Czech Republic and Slovakia attended the games as independent nations for the first time since the breakup of Czechoslovakia, while the rest of the nations that made their Summer Olympic debut were formerly part of the Soviet Union.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] 10,339 athletes from 197 NOCs participated in the 1996 Summer Olympics.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The ceremony began with a 60-second countdown, which included footage from all of the previous Olympic Games at twenty-two seconds.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] There was then a flashback to the closing ceremony of the 1992 Olympics in Barcelona, showing the then president of the IOC, Juan Antonio Samaranch, inviting the athletes to compete in Atlanta in 1996.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Then, spirits ascended in the northwest corner of the stadium, each representing one of the colors in the Olympic rings.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The spirits called the tribes of the world which, after mixed percussion, formed the Olympic rings while the youth of Atlanta formed the number 100.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Famed film score composer John Williams wrote the official overture for the 1996 Olympics, called "Summon the Heroes"; this was his second overture for Olympic games, the first being "Olympic Fanfare and Theme" written for the 1984 Summer Olympics.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Céline Dion performed David Foster's official 1996 Olympics song "The Power of the Dream", accompanied by Foster on the piano, the Atlanta Symphony Orchestra and the Centennial Choir (comprising Morehouse College Glee Club, Spelman College Glee Club and the Atlanta Symphony Orchestra Chorus).
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Gladys Knight sang Georgia's official state song, "Georgia on My Mind".
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] There was another showcase entitled "Summertime" which focused on Atlanta and the Old South, emphasizing its beauty, spirit, music, history, culture, and rebirth after the American Civil War.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The ceremony also featured a memorable dance tribute to the athletes and to the goddesses of victory of the ancient Greek Olympics, using silhouette imagery.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The accompanying music, "The Tradition of the Games", was composed by Basil Poledouris.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Muhammad Ali lit the Olympic cauldron and later received a replacement gold medal for his boxing victory in the 1960 Summer Olympics.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] For the torch ceremony, more than 10,000 Olympic torches were manufactured by the American Meter Company, electroplated by Klein Plating Works, and polished by Erie Plating Company.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Each torch weighed about 3.5 pounds (1.6 kg) and was made primarily of aluminum, with a Georgia pecan wood handle and gold ornamentation.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The city of Savannah, Georgia, host of the yachting events, also held their own opening ceremony on the first day of their competitions.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The event was headlined by a performance by country musician Trisha Yearwood.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The 1996 Summer Olympic program featured 271 events in 26 sports.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Softball, beach volleyball and mountain biking debuted on the Olympic program, together with women's football, lightweight events in rowing, Women's 4 × 200 metre freestyle relay in swimming, the Women's épée in fencing and the group all-around event in rhythmic gymnastics.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1996 Games.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Domestic network NBC bought the broadcasting rights for US$456 million.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The European Broadcasting Union paid US$240 million.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The 1996 Olympics were marred by the Centennial Olympic Park bombing, which occurred on July 27.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Security guard Richard Jewell discovered the pipe bomb and immediately notified law enforcement, helping to evacuate as many people as possible from the area before it exploded.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Although Jewell's quick actions are credited for saving many lives, the bombing killed spectator Alice Hawthorne, wounded 111 others, and caused the death of Melih Uzunyol by a heart attack.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Jewell was later considered a suspect in the bombing but was never charged, and he was cleared in October 1996.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Fugitive Eric Rudolph was arrested in May 2003 and charged with the Olympic Park bombing as well as the bombings of two abortion clinics and a gay nightclub.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Preparations for the Olympics lasted more than seven years and had an economic impact of at least US$5.14 billion.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Over two million visitors came to Atlanta, and approximately 3.5 billion people around the world watched at least some of the events on television.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Although marred by the tragedy of the Centennial Olympic Park bombing, the Games were a financial success, due in part to TV rights contracts and sponsorships at record levels.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Atlanta also set a new record for the most tickets sold at a single Games (8.3 million), and held it until 2024.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Beyond international recognition, the Games resulted in many modern infrastructure improvements.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The mid-rise dormitories built for the Olympic Village, which became the first residential housing for Georgia State University (Georgia State Village), are now used by the Georgia Institute of Technology (North Avenue Apartments).
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] As designed, the Centennial Olympic Stadium was converted into Turner Field after the Paralympics, which became the home of the Atlanta Braves Major League Baseball team from 1997 to 2016.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The Braves' former home, Atlanta–Fulton County Stadium, was demolished in 1997 and the site became a parking lot for Turner Field; the Omni Coliseum was demolished the same year to make way for State Farm Arena.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The city's permanent memorial to the 1996 Olympics is Centennial Olympic Park, which was built as a focal point for the Games.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The park initiated a revitalization of the surrounding area and now serves as the hub for Atlanta's tourism district.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] In November 2016, a commemorative plaque was unveiled for Centennial Olympic Park to honor the 20th anniversary of the Games.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Following the Braves' departure from Turner Field to Truist Park in 2017, Georgia State University acquired the former Olympic Stadium and surrounding parking lots.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] It reconfigured the stadium for a second time into Center Parc Stadium for its college football team.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The 1996 Olympic cauldron was originally built and placed at the intersection of Fulton Street and Capitol Avenue, near the Centennial Olympic Stadium.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] After the Paralympics, in order to make room for the stadium conversion, the Olympic cauldron was moved (except its ramp, which was demolished) to the intersection of Capitol Avenue and Fulton Street in 1997, where it has stayed since.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Since Georgia State University's acquisition of the former Olympic Stadium and surrounding lots, there has been proposals and growing calls to move the Olympic cauldron to Centennial Olympic Park.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The Olympic cauldron was re-lit in February 2020 for the 2020 U.S.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The 1996 Olympics are the most recent edition of the Summer Olympics to be held in the United States.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Los Angeles will host the 2028 Summer Olympics, 32 years after the Games were held in Atlanta.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] In 1997, Athens was awarded the 2004 Summer Olympics.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Along with addressing the shortcomings of its 1996 bid, it was lauded for its efforts to promote the traditional values of the Olympic Games, which some IOC observers felt had been lost due to the over-commercialization of the 1996 Games.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] However, the 2004 Games heavily relied on public funding and eventually failed to make a profit, which some have claimed contributed to the financial crisis in Greece.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The financial struggles faced by many later Games, such as the 2006 Winter Olympics in Turin and the 2016 Summer Olympics in Rio de Janeiro, have caused some to offer more positive reappraisals of the management of the 1996 Summer Games.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] Former JPMorgan Chase president (and torchbearer) Kabir Sehgal noted that in contrast to many later Olympics, those of 1996 were financially viable, had a positive economic impact on the city, and most of the facilities constructed continued to be used after the Games.
[src:ballpark/1996-summer-olympics] The 2028 Summer Olympics in Los Angeles will rely almost entirely on private funding, with the city of Los Angeles and state of California each intending to provide up to $250 million in funding in the event of shortfalls, and the U.S. federal government providing funding solely for security.
[src:ballpark/2019-miami-open] The **2019 Miami Open** (sponsored by Itaú) was a professional men and women's tennis tournament played on outdoor hard courts that started on March 18, 2019, and ended on March 31, 2019.
[src:ballpark/2019-miami-open] It was the 35th edition of the Miami Open, and part of the Masters 1000 category on the 2019 ATP Tour, and of the Premier Mandatory category on the 2019 WTA Tour.
[src:ballpark/2019-miami-open] This was the first time the tournament took place at the Hard Rock Stadium in Miami Gardens, Florida, United States.
[src:ballpark/2019-miami-open] Rankings and seedings are based on ATP rankings as of March 18, 2019.
[src:ballpark/2019-miami-open] † The player did not qualify for the tournament in 2018.
[src:ballpark/2019-miami-open] Accordingly, points for his 18th best result are deducted instead.
[src:ballpark/2019-miami-open] The following players would have been seeded, but they withdrew from the event.
[src:ballpark/2019-miami-open] † The player is entitled to use an exemption to skip the tournament and substitute his 18th best result (45 points in each case) in its stead. ‡ The player did not qualify for the main draw based on his ranking at the entry cutoff date and only withdrew from the alternates list.
[src:ballpark/2019-miami-open] Accordingly, no points are deducted for the withdrawal.
[src:ballpark/2019-miami-open] Seedings are based on WTA rankings as of March 4, 2019.
[src:ballpark/2019-miami-open] Rankings and points before are as of March 18, 2019.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] A **ballpark**, or **baseball park**, is a type of sports venue where baseball is played.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] The playing field is divided into two field sections called the infield and the outfield.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] The infield is an area whose dimensions are rigidly defined in part based on the placement of bases, and the outfield is where dimensions can vary widely from ballpark to ballpark.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] A larger ballpark may also be called a **baseball stadium** because it shares characteristics of other stadiums.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] A baseball field can be referred to as a diamond.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] The infield is a rigidly structured diamond of dirt and grass containing the three bases, home plate, and the pitcher's mound.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] The space between the bases and home is normally a grass surface, save for the dirt mound in the center.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] Some ballparks have grass or artificial turf between the bases, and dirt only around the bases and pitcher's mound.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] Others, such as Koshien Stadium in Hyōgo Prefecture, Japan, have an infield of entirely dirt.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] Two white lines extend from the home plate area, aligned with the first and third bases.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] These are the *foul lines* or *base lines*, usually differentiated by referring to them as the first base line, or the third base line.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] If a ball hit by the batter lands outside of the space between these two lines or rolls out of this space before reaching first or third base, the ball is "foul" (meaning it is dead and the play is over).
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] If it lands between or on the lines, it is "fair".
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] At the end of the lines are two foul poles, which help the umpires judge whether a ball is fair or foul.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] These "foul poles" are actually in fair territory, so a ball that hits them on the fly is a home run (if hit on the bounce, it is instead an automatic double).
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] On either side of home plate are the two batter's boxes (left-handed and right-handed.) This is where the batter stands when at bat.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] Behind home is the catcher's box, where the catcher and the home plate umpire stand.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] Next to the first and third base are two coaches' boxes, where the first and third base coaches guide the baserunners, generally with gestures or shouts.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] As the baserunner faces away from the outfield when running from second base to third, they cannot see where the ball is and must look to the third base coach on whether to run, stop, or slide.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] Farther from the infield on either side are the dugouts, where the teams and coaches sit when they're not on the field.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] They are named such because, at the professional levels, this seating is below the level of the playing field to not block the view from prime spectator seating locations.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] In amateur parks, the dugouts may be above-ground wooden or CMU structures with seating inside, or simply benches behind a chain-link fence.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] Beyond the infield and between the foul lines is a large grass outfield, generally twice the depth of the infield.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] The playing field is bordered by fences of varying heights.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] The infield fences are in foul territory, and a ball hit over them is not a home run; consequently, they are often lower than the outfield fences to provide a better view for spectators.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] Sometimes, the outfield fence is made higher in certain areas to compensate for close proximity to the batter.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] In many parks, the field is surrounded by an area roughly 10 feet (3.0 m) wide made of dirt or rubberized track surface called a "warning track".
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] In the 1937 refurbishment of the original Yankee Stadium, a running track that ran the perimeter of the field was incorporated into the field of play as the first warning track.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] MLB formalized the warning track as a requirement in 1949.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] Beyond the outfield fence in professional parks is an area called the batter's eye.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] To ensure the batter can see the white ball, the batter's eye contains no seating and is darker in color.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] The batter's eye area can be anything from a dark wall to a grassy slope.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] Most major league ballparks are oriented with the central axis (home plate through second base through center field) of the playing field running toward the north or east or some direction between.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] Major League Baseball Rule 1.04 states that it is "desirable" (but not required) that the central axis run east-northeast (about 22 degrees north of east).
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] This is to prevent the setting sun from being in the batter's eyes.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] In practice, major league parks vary up to about 90 degrees from east-northeast in either direction, but none face west, except for a few which are oriented just slightly west of straight north.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] (Left-handed pitchers are called "southpaws", and indeed the pitcher's left hand is toward the south in the usual park layout, and this has often been cited as the source of the appellation.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] Today, in Major League Baseball, a multi-tiered seating area, a grandstand, surrounds the infield.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] How far this seating extends down the baselines or around the foul poles varies from park to park.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] In minor league parks, the grandstands are notably smaller, proportional to expected sizes of crowds compared with the major leagues.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] The seating beyond the outfield fence generally differs from the grandstand, though some multi-purpose or jewel box parks have the grandstand surround the entire field.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] This area could contain inexpensive bleacher seats, smaller grandstands, or simply inclined seating.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] In local ballparks, there are often simply a set or two of aluminum bleachers on the first-base and third-base sides.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] Distinctive from "goal games" such as football and basketball, which have fixed-size playing areas, the infield is the only rigidly laid-out part of the field.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] Like its English relative, cricket, there is significant flexibility in the shape and size of the rest of the playing area.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] Baseball leagues may specify a minimum distance from home plate to the outfield fences.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] Generally, the higher the skill level, the deeper the minimum dimensions must be, to prevent an excess of home runs.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] In the major leagues, a rule was passed in 1958 that compelled any new fields built after that point to have a minimum distance of 325 feet (99 m) from home plate to the fences in left and right field, and 400 feet (120 m) to center.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] This rule was passed to avoid situations like the Los Angeles Coliseum, which was 251 ft (77 m). down the left field line.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] However, with the opening of Baltimore's Camden Yards (1992), the "minimum distance" rule began to be ignored.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] One factor may be that the quaint, "retro" look of Camden Yards, with its irregular measurements, proved to be very popular, along with a traditionalist backlash against the symmetrical, multi-purpose, "cookie-cutter" stadiums.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] Since the opening of Camden Yards, many other "retro" stadiums have been built, each with asymmetrical fences.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] These distances vary from park to park, and can even change drastically in the same park.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] One of the most famous examples is the original Yankee Stadium, whose odd-shaped plot of land caused right field to be over 100 feet (30 m) shorter than left, although this difference lessened over time.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] The rectangular Polo Grounds had extremely short distance down the lines, 258 ft (79 m). to right and 280 ft (85 m). to left.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] In contrast, the deepest part of center field was nearly 500 ft (150 m). from home plate.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] Older ballparks, such as Fenway Park, were grandfathered in and allowed to keep their original dimensions.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] Also, new parks have sometimes received special dispensation to deviate from these rules.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] For instance, the second Yankee Stadium, built 2009, used the same dimensions as the original Yankee Stadium.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] The heights of the fences can also vary greatly, the most famous example being the 37-foot (11 m)-high Green Monster in Fenway Park's left field.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] Such tall fences are often used to stop easy home runs in a section of the ballpark where the distances from home are shorter, or where there is little space between the field and the street beyond.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] Some in-play scoreboards and high fences reached 50 to 60 feet (18 m), whereas a few outfields were even lined with hedges rather than normal fences or walls.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] Humphrey Metrodome, when set up for baseball, had a 23-foot (7.0 m) right field "fence" that was actually a relatively thin blue plastic sheet covering folded up football seats.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] It was often called a "baggie" or "Hefty bag".
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] Some ballparks have irregularly shaped fences.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] Ballparks may have round swooping fences or rigidly angled fences, or possibly a significant change in direction or irregular angle.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] For example, the center field stands and the left field stands at Fenway Park meet at an uneven angle, creating an indentation (called "the triangle") that angles sharply back into the stands.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] In Citi Field and Oracle Park, part of the right field fence juts unevenly into the outfield as if the builders were trying to create an unpredictable ricochet effect for balls hit against it.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] Some "retro" parks, such as Globe Life Park in Arlington, throw in a sudden and small inward turn (often referred to as a jog) just to give a little quirkiness to the design.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] Milwaukee's Miller Park was designed, with the help of former player Robin Yount, to promote extra base hits.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] Originally (mostly in the old jewel box parks) these variations resulted from the shape of the property where the park was constructed.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] If there was a street beyond left field, the distance to the left field fence would be shorter, and if the distance was too short, the fence would be higher.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] For example, in the old Griffith Stadium in Washington, D.C., part of center field had to be built around a cluster of apartment houses and the result was a rather large angular indentation in the left-center field fence.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] Now, these variations are mostly influenced by the specifications and whims of the designers.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] New "retro" parks, which try to recapture the feel of the jewel box parks, are often designed to have these quirks.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] Baseball was originally played in open fields or public parks.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] The genesis of modern baseball is conventionally connected with Elysian Fields in Hoboken, New Jersey, a large public park where the businessmen of New York City gathered from time to time to play organized baseball games and cricket matches, starting around the mid-1840s.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] The name "Field" or "Park" was typically attached to the names of the early ballparks.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] With the beginnings of professional baseball, the ballfield became part of a complex including fixed spectator seating areas, and an enclosure to restrict access to paying customers, as with a fairgrounds.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] The name "Grounds" began to be attached to ballparks, starting with the Union Grounds in 1862.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] The suffixes "Field" and "Park" were still used, but many professional ballparks were "Grounds".
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] The last major league "Grounds" was the Polo Grounds in New York City, which was razed in 1964.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] The term "stadium" has been used since ancient times, typically for a running track and its seating area.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] As college football gained in popularity, the smaller college playing fields and running tracks (which also frequently had the suffix "Field") gave way to large stadiums, many of them built during the sport's "boom" of the 1920s.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] Major league baseball enjoyed a similar boom.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] One of the first major league ballparks to be called a "stadium" was actually the Polo Grounds, which was temporarily renamed Brush Stadium from its reconstruction in 1911 until the death of owner John T.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] By then, the most famous baseball "stadium" of them all had been constructed: Yankee Stadium.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] From that point until the retro building boom of the 1990s, the suffix "Stadium" was used for almost every new major league venue, and was sometimes applied to the old ones, such as Shibe Park, which was renamed Connie Mack Stadium in 1954.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] The suffix "Dome" was also used for the indoor stadiums constructed from the 1960s onward.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] The retro era of the 1990s and early 2000s saw some venues return to using "park" in a stadium's name, even in domed structures such as T-Mobile Park and American Family Field (which opened with the name Miller Park).
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] There is little consistency in the choice between "Field" and "Park".
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] For example, Houston's Daikin Park was originally named "Enron Field".
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] Seating area design of stadiums is affected by many variables, including required capacity, audience access, and road traffic.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] Early ballparks like Elysian Fields were a far distance from the city center.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] Each game was an event, and fans traveled by public transit to watch the game.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] With the growth of professional leagues, and consequent growth in the quantity of games, each game became less of an event, and fan convenience became more important.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] Many professional ballparks were built either near the city center, or in working-class neighborhoods, based on the expected economic level of the average fan.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] Consequently, the classic ballparks typically had little space for automobiles, as it was expected that most fans would take mass transit to the games, a situation that still prevails at Boston's Fenway Park and Chicago's Wrigley Field, for example.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] Some early ballparks, such as Brooklyn's Eastern Park, were abandoned because the trolley lines did not go out far enough and the team was not performing well enough for people to tolerate the inconvenience.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] As fans became more affluent, and especially as they moved to the suburbs and bought cars, the lack of parking became an important issue.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] Some ballparks remedied this problem through the construction of parking garages in the vicinity, or building new ballparks with ample parking.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] Others built ballparks in the suburbs, typically with large parking areas.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] The ballpark/stadium thus became an "island" in an "ocean" of parking space.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p01] The modern "retro" trend strives to support multiple modes of transport, by having an urban location with available parking and accessibility by public transport.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] The first professional baseball venues were large **wooden ballparks** with seats mounted on wood platforms.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Although known for being constructed out of wood, they featured iron columns for better support.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Some included one tier of inclined seating, topped with either a flat roof or, in some instances, a small upper tier.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] The outfield was bordered by tall walls or fences covered in advertisements, much like today's minor league parks.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] These advertisements were sometimes fronted with bleacher seats, or "bleaching boards".
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Wood, while prone to decomposition, was a relatively inexpensive material.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] However, the use of wood as the primary material presented a major problem, especially as baseball continued to thrive.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Over time, the wooden stands aged and dried.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Many parks caught fire, and some were leveled completely.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] This problem, along with the popularization of baseball and expectations for long-term use of the parks were major factors that drove the transition to the new standard materials for ballparks: steel and concrete.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Some famous wooden parks, such as the Polo Grounds III in New York and National League Park in Philadelphia, burned and were rebuilt with fire-resistant materials (Polo Grounds IV and Baker Bowl).
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Others were simply abandoned in favor of new structures built elsewhere.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] These new fire-resistant parks often lasted for many decades, and (retrospectively) came to be known as "jewel boxes".
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] There are no more professional ballparks in existence left with this architectural trend, with the last one, Oriole Park V, burning down in 1944.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] The earliest ballparks built or rebuilt of reinforced concrete, brick, and steel are now known as the **jewel box ballparks** or **classic parks**.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Two-tiered grandstands became much more prevalent in this era, as well.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] The Baker Bowl in Philadelphia, which opened in 1895, was the first to use steel and brick as the primary construction materials and included a cantilevered upper deck seating area that hung out over the lower seating area.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Although it did not use reinforced concrete in its construction, Baker Bowl is considered the first of the jewel box parks.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] The first to use reinforced concrete was Shibe Park, which opened in 1909, also in Philadelphia.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] The upper decks were typically held up by steel pillars that obstructed the view from some seats in the lower level.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] However, because of the supports used, the upper decks could come very close to the field.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] The two-tiered design was the standard for decades, until the New York Yankees built Yankee Stadium.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] To accommodate the large crowds Babe Ruth drew, Yankee Stadium was built with three tiers.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] This became the new standard until some recently built parks reverted to two, including PNC Park in 2001.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Most jewel box parks were built to fit the constraints of actual city blocks, often resulting in significantly asymmetrical outfield dimensions and large outfield walls to prevent easy home runs.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Notable examples included League Park in Cleveland, which had a 40-foot (12 m)-tall wall in right field, and the Green Monster, the 37-foot (11 m)-tall left field wall at Fenway Park in Boston.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Notable exceptions include Shibe Park and Comiskey Park, which were built on rectangular city blocks that were large enough to accommodate symmetrical left and right fields.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Other sports, such as soccer and football, were often played at these sites (Yankee Stadium, for example, was designed to accommodate football).
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] In contrast to the later multi-purpose parks, the seats were generally angled in a configuration suitable for baseball.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] The "retro" ballparks built in the 1990s and beyond are an attempt to capture the feel of the jewel box parks.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] The only jewel box parks still used by Major League Baseball are Fenway Park and Wrigley Field.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] From the 1960s until the arrival of retro parks in 1992, baseball built many **multi-purpose ballparks**.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Also derisively known as "concrete donuts", "cookie-cutters", or "giant ashtrays", they were usually tall and circular or square structures made entirely of, usually bare, reinforced concrete.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] The parks were built to hold baseball, but also were able to host other sports, such as football and soccer.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] One of the earliest baseball stadiums that incorporated this type of design was Cleveland Stadium (built 1932), which featured an oval grandstand that was more friendly to goal-centered sports like football.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] A park built to suit all sports well, which was co-owned by the teams or the city, seemed advantageous to all, especially because it was less expensive to maintain one stadium rather than two.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Some parks that were originally built for one sport were renovated to accommodate multiple sports.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] The shape of the parks generally depended on the original use.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Ballparks that were renovated to accommodate football, like Candlestick Park and Anaheim Stadium, were usually asymmetrically shaped.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Football stadiums that were renovated to accommodate baseball, like Sun Life Stadium and Mile High Stadium, were usually of a rectangular shape, though Mile High actually started its life in 1948 as a Minor League Baseball park known as Bears Stadium.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Parks that were built to serve both were usually circular and completely enclosed on all sides.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] These were the parks that gained multi-purpose parks the reputation as bland cookie-cutter structures.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] The first of these parks was DC Stadium (renamed RFK Stadium in 1969) in the District of Columbia.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] RFK is unique in that it hosted two different baseball teams, and that it was the first to *originally* be intended for multiple sports.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] A notable variant among the cookie-cutter stadia was Shea Stadium.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Its grandstand extended just beyond the foul poles and did not completely enclose the field.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Plans were made to enclose the grandstand and build a dome, but engineers discovered that the structure could not handle the load of the proposed dome.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Thus, the area behind the outfield fence remained open.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] One major innovation of the multi-purpose parks was the cantilevered upper deck.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] In earlier ballparks, the columns used to support the upper decks obstructed the view from some seats in the lower deck.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] In the new design, the upper decks were extended upwards and the columns were removed.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] However, even though the extension counterbalanced some of the weight, the upper decks could no longer extend as close to the field and had to be moved back.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Also, the roofs could no longer be as large, and often only covered the top 15 or so rows.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Besides the drawbacks of the cantilever design, there were other issues with these parks.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] With few exceptions, seating was angled to face the center of the field of play, rather than home plate.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] The furthest seats in these parks were 500 feet (150 m) or more from the plate.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] The capacities of these stadiums were larger than previous baseball stadiums.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Typical game attendance did not fill the stadiums.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Due to the rectangular shape needed for football or soccer, outfield dimensions were generally symmetrical, and even seats at field level down the lines could be far from the action.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Multi-purpose stadiums also posed issues for their non-baseball tenants.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] The "cookie-cutters" with swiveling, field-level sections proved problematic.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Because the front rows were too close to the field, the fans had difficulty seeing over the football benches.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] This was evident in the movable seating sections in RFK Stadium.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] The first ten rows of the football configuration were practically at field level, and fans in those sections often stood up on their seats to get a better view.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Other stadiums overcame this simply by covering those seats, not bothering to sell them.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Despite being cost-effective, these problems eventually caused the parks to become unfashionable.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] The multi-purpose architecture reached a climax when Toronto's SkyDome (now Rogers Centre) opened in 1989.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] It had state-of-the-art amenities including a retractable roof, hotel, and a restaurant behind the outfield from where patrons could view the games.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Rogers Centre was renovated into a baseball only stadium from 2022 to 2024.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] There are no more purely multi-purpose parks still in use today, with the Oakland Coliseum having been the last one in use.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] The Athletics moved out of Oakland Coliseum in 2024 and will play at West Sacramento's Sutter Health Park for three seasons as a new dedicated facility of their own is built in Las Vegas.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Their former co-tenants, the NFL Oakland Raiders, moved to Las Vegas in 2020 and into Allegiant Stadium.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] An important type of ballpark is the **indoor park**.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] These parks are covered with a fixed roof, usually a hard concrete dome.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] The reasons to build indoor parks are varied.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] The Astrodome, the first indoor sports stadium ever built, was built to escape the hot and very humid climate of Houston and the Kingdome was built to escape Seattle's constant fall and winter rains.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] In Japan, domed stadiums were built to escape frequently rainy climates, as well as extreme snowfall in Sapporo.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] There is little to no natural light in these parks, necessitating the use of one of the most distinguishing aspects of an indoor park: artificial turf.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Since there was not enough light to grow grass, artificial turf is installed, and this affected the game.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Artificial turf is harder, and thus a ball hit on the ground moves faster and bounces higher.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] This, coupled with the usually dull white or gray roofs that could camouflage a fly ball, causing what Twins fans called a "dome-field advantage".
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] A park of note is Olympic Stadium in Montreal.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] The park was designed with a large tower that loomed over top.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Cables came down from the top of the tower to connect to the large oval center of the roof.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] This oval center was supposed to be lifted by the cables, opening the park up if the weather was pleasant.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] However, the mechanism never worked correctly, and what was supposed to be a retractable roof was initially not used, then used for only a short period of time, and later replaced with a permanently fixed roof, making the stadium a strictly indoor facility.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Humphrey Metrodome in Minneapolis, which instead of a rigid masonry roof was covered by inflatable fiberglass sheeting, held up by air pressure.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] A drawback to this design, at least in Minnesota's severe winter climate, was revealed when the dome collapsed three times in its first three years of operation due to accumulated snow.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] The Tokyo Dome has a similar roof; due to Tokyo's considerably milder winter climate, that stadium has not had the Metrodome's snow-related issues.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] The first generation of indoor parks faced many of the same problems of the multi-purpose parks.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Tropicana Field is the only indoor-only or fixed-dome park built specifically for baseball and the only one left hosting a Major League Baseball team, and is scheduled to be replaced in the near future.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] The new ballpark for the Las Vegas Athletics is slated to have a fixed roof with a window to allow natural light in, like Allegiant Stadium.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Japan still has several fixed-dome parks designed primarily for baseball.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] One of these, the Sapporo Dome, features two separate playing surfaces.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Baseball is played on a permanently installed artificial surface within the dome, while a permanent grass pitch is attached to the structure and mechanically slid into the dome for use in soccer matches.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Also used by the Hanshin Tigers for season openers and August home games when their normal home of Koshien Stadium is being used for national high school tournaments.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Occasionally used by two other NPB teams, the Kintetsu Buffaloes and Orix BlueWave (now merged into the Orix Buffaloes).
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] While most teams turned to multi-purpose parks, some built baseball-only parks.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] While these **modern ballparks** shirked some of the conventions of multi-purpose parks, they did include some of the new features.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] The most notable influences were the cantilevered upper decks, the use of seating colors other than green, fairly plain concrete exteriors, and symmetrical outfields.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] While the multi-purpose parks have become all but extinct, some modern parks, such as Dodger Stadium and Kauffman Stadium, have been hailed for aging beautifully.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Rather than build new parks, the teams have decided instead to renovate the current structures, adding a few newer conveniences.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Several of the modern parks built as such have remained in use, with no indication of being demolished.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] While Cleveland Stadium is the ancestor to the multi-purpose ballpark, the ancestor of the modern ballpark is Milwaukee County Stadium.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] It was the first to feature a symmetrical, round outfield fence.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] It also featured the rounded V-shaped grandstand and colorful seats that are common among modern parks.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Coincidentally, it would have been one of the earlier examples of a converted park as well.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] It was supposed to replace a minor league facility, and serve as home of the minor league team until a major league franchise could be lured to the city.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] However, the Braves came to Milwaukee earlier than expected, and the minor league team never played in the stadium.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] The first two truly modern ballparks were built by the two New York teams who moved to California, the Giants and the Dodgers.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Candlestick Park was created first, but was converted to a multi-purpose park to accommodate the 49ers.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Dodger Stadium has been upgraded a number of times, but remains baseball-only and its original design is still largely intact.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Anaheim Stadium, which was initially modeled closely on Dodger Stadium, was expanded for football, but once the Rams departed, most of the extra outfield seating was peeled back, returning the structure to something closer to its original design.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] The original Yankee Stadium is an exceptional case.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Yankee Stadium was originally built as a jewel box park, albeit a very large one.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] It was showing its age in the 1970s, and the stadium was extensively renovated during 1973–1975, converting it into more of a modern style ballpark.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Many of the characteristics that defined it as a classical jewel box were retained, so the remodeled Stadium straddled both categories.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Rogers Centre, which has a retractable roof and Tropicana Field, which has a fixed roof, can also be considered modern ballparks.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Originally built as a multi-purpose stadium, Rogers Centre has been renovated as a baseball only park, while Tropicana Field was built with the intent to attract an MLB team to the Tampa Bay area.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] New Comiskey Park (now Rate Field) was the last modern ballpark to be built in North America.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] A series of renovations have been made to make it appear more like a retro-classic ballpark.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] Although they were purposefully built for baseball, some of these stadiums also hosted professional soccer and football teams at times.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] The Minnesota Vikings played at Metropolitan Stadium during the Twins' entire tenure there, and the Green Bay Packers played a few home games at Milwaukee County Stadium every year from 1953 through 1994.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p02] A few of them, including Metropolitan Stadium, also hosted NASL teams during the 1970s.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] The indoor parks were built for several different reasons, chief among those weather.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] However, as multi-purpose parks became unfashionable, so did indoor parks.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] This led to the creation of **retractable-roof parks**.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] These allowed shelter from the elements, but still could be open when the weather was pleasant.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] To be able to support the roof, most were closed in on all sides like multi-purpose and indoor parks.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Because the roof needs to go somewhere when not covering the field, a distinguishing characteristic of the retractable roof park is a large extension of the interior spaces to either one side of the field or both sides that the roof sits on when retracted.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] The only exception to this is American Family Field, whose fan-shaped roof folds in upon itself and hangs behind the stands down the foul lines.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Often, when retracted, the roof still hangs over the field, casting large shadows.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] This is countered at American Family Field by large panes of glass under the roof.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] While most stadiums seal up when the roof is closed, others remain partially open, such as T-Mobile Park, whose roof acts as an "umbrella" to shield from Seattle's frequently rainy weather.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Pittsburgh's Civic Arena was the first sports building in the world with a retractable roof; however, the building was originally constructed for the Pittsburgh Civic Light Opera, which moved out in 1969 due to dissatisfaction with the acoustics in the arena.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] The arena's long-term tenants, the NHL's Pittsburgh Penguins, never played with the roof open, and the arena itself was never used for baseball (and was too small to be used for that sport).
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] While Montreal's Olympic Stadium was the first baseball park to have a retractable roof, the roof was plagued by numerous problems, and was never fully used.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] This made Rogers Centre the first fully functional retractable-roof park.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] It managed to succeed where Olympic Stadium failed, building a multi-section roof that folded upon itself, retracting over the hotel in center field.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Retractable-roof parks can vary greatly in style, from the utilitarian (Rogers Centre), to those infused with retro elements (such as Daikin Park), to the contemporary (loanDepot Park).
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] The style of each park reflects the popular architecture of the era in which it was built.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] (This differs from indoor ballparks, all of which were built during the time of multi-purpose parks, and thus reflected the same "flying-saucer" style.) When Rogers Centre opened in 1989, baseball was near the end of the modern and multi-purpose era.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Chase Field, T-Mobile Park, Daikin Park, and American Family Field all opened in the middle of the retro era.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] When loanDepot Park opened in 2012 as Marlins Park, it introduced a new and different style, and perhaps the beginning of a new era.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] The Texas Rangers built Globe Life Field in the retro style similar to their previous ballpark, Globe Life Park.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Therefore, the term "retractable-roof ballpark/stadium" is not a description of the overall architectural style of the building, but of the functional aspect of it.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] For this reason, retractable-roof parks are also dual-listed in style-based types of ballparks.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] For example, the four retractable-roof parks built in the United States during the retro era are also considered to be retro-modern ballparks.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] HOK Sport, now known as Populous, designed Sahlen Field in Buffalo to attract a major league franchise to the city.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] HOK Sport would take what they learned in Buffalo about styling a **retro-classic ballpark**, or **retro/jewel box ballpark**, to their major league project in Baltimore.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] In 1992, Oriole Park at Camden Yards opened in Baltimore in a similar style and colour to a jewel box park, but with more features and accommodations.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] The ballpark also has a modern, stepped-deck layout, columns removed, and fencing changed.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Since Camden Yards opened, two-thirds of all major league teams have opened new ballparks, each of which contain unique features.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] The most important feature was that they were built primarily for baseball, although these venues have also hosted football, soccer and ice hockey games.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Turner Field was originally constructed as Centennial Olympic Stadium for the 1996 Summer Olympics and was retrofitted to baseball the following year.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Rate Field was the last modern park built in 1991 and was viewed as obsolete a year after opening.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] The White Sox responded with a series of retro-classic style renovations, such as roofing changes, asymmetrical fencing, and a dark green colour scheme.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Upper deck seating was also reduced to eliminate less purchased seating locations.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] The most recent retro-classic ballparks were built in New York City.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Queens' Citi Field is modeled after Ebbets Field, and the Bronx's Yankee Stadium is modeled after the pre-renovation "House that Ruth Built".
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Teams are now trending away from the retro-classic look and are instead building retro-modern and contemporary ballparks.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Turner Field was the first retro-classic park replaced, as the Atlanta Braves moved to Truist Park in 2017, while the Texas Rangers moved from Globe Life Park in Arlington to the retractable-roof Globe Life Field in 2020.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Rate Field is planned to be replaced with a new ballpark in the near future.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] While Camden Yards influenced nearly every ballpark built after it, not all fully adhere to its design.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Those that deviate to incorporate more modern-looking elements are called **retro-modern ballparks**.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Progressive Field, originally Jacobs Field, was built two years after Camden Yards, and featured the angular, asymmetrical fences of varying heights, a smaller upper deck, stepped tiers, and an unobtrusive singular color scheme.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] While the interior has all the hallmarks of a retro park, the exterior did not feature the look of the jewel box parks.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] It could not truly be called a retro-classic park.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Many of today's parks have followed in this second school of retro.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Rather than brick, the exteriors heavily feature white- or gray-painted steel.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] If there is any masonry, it is sandstone or limestone.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Some feature progressive elements such as curtain walls, or retractable roofs.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Angel Stadium has seen many changes throughout the years.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] It was originally a modern park, similar to the Angels' previous home, Dodger Stadium.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] When the NFL's Los Angeles Rams left the Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum in 1980 and set up shop in what was then Anaheim Stadium, the first round of renovations began.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] The grandstand was expanded to completely enclose the stadium, turning it into a multi-purpose park.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] The Rams left in 1994, leaving the Angels alone in the large, 65,000-seat stadium.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] After a two-year renovation, the steel was painted green, and what concrete remained was painted sandstone, including the sweeping curve of the entrance plaza.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] The seating configuration was significantly altered, most notably by tearing out most of the outfield seating except for parts of the lower decks in left and right fields, to more closely resemble the original design from the park's first 15 years.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] The finished product in 1998 was a retro-modern ballpark.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] In the same year, Chase Field opened as Bank One Ballpark for the expansion Arizona Diamondbacks, it incorporated a retractable roof and a swimming pool—elements that did not exist in jewel-box ballparks.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Despite the absence of MLB history in the Phoenix area and an overwhelming roof design, much of the interior was still built with all of the hallmarks of retro, similar to Progressive Field.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Although Chase Field was not the first retractable-roof ballpark in history, it was the first in a wave of four retractable-roof ballparks (opening within just four years) to follow the retro-modern pattern.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] During the second decade of retro, Petco Park and Kauffman Stadium followed the construction and renovation concepts of Progressive Field and Angel Stadium, respectively.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Meanwhile, the period saw another subset of three new retro-modern stadiums that pushed away from classic parks even more.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] When Great American Ball Park opened in 2003, it featured a contemporary-looking, glass-wrapped facade.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Such prominent use of elements that were unfamiliar even to pre-1992 modern stadiums signaled that some stadium planners were more willing to incorporate designs that looked into the 21st century as much as they did the 20th.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Five years later, Nationals Park built off Cincinnati's design, making yet more liberal use of glass along with white concrete that would not clash with architecture in the District.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Nationals Park became the first stadium to go green while still offering all of the amenities—another concept that looked ahead instead of behind.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] The retro-modern style climaxed in 2010 with the sculptured, contemporary exterior and canopy of Target Field, rendering it almost unrecognizable from the outside.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Its cantilevered glass on top of a limestone base was designed partly to functionally fit the tiny 8-acre plot in the middle of a bustling transportation interchange.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] But the principal architect of Target Field, Earl Santee of Populous, said that the exterior was also an artistic interpretation of the culture of Minnesotans: a dichotomy of cosmopolitan and natural.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Designing the building as a metaphor for people was a different way of thinking about ballpark architecture.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Subsequent retro-contemporary ballparks transitioned away from the architectural characteristics of both jewel-box and modern-style stadiums.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] While these venues incorporate contemporary amenities and field layouts, they maintain traditional aesthetic elements.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Characteristic retro-style features include asymmetrical outfield fences and monochromatic color schemes, frequently utilizing forest green.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Prior to the start of the 2012 baseball season, *USA Today* noted that new Marlins Park would "perhaps provide a coda to the postmodern Camden Yards era".
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] After two decades of the retro style dominating ballpark architecture, a new type of design emerged in 2012 with the opening of the venue now known as LoanDepot Park, snapping the consecutive streak of 20 new (plus 3 renovated) MLB retro stadiums.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] This latest style's purpose is to make the fan experience the present-day culture of the stadium's surrounding city or area, and rejects the basic notion of retro.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Es Con Field Hokkaido, a ballpark in a similar style built for the Hokkaido Nippon-Ham Fighters of Nippon Professional Baseball, opened in 2023.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] The new ballpark for the Las Vegas Athletics was purposely designed to fit into the atmosphere of the surrounding Las Vegas Strip.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] The expansion teams of the 1960s led to the emergence of two distinct subsets of parks in the major leagues: **temporary ballparks** and **converted ballparks**.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Temporary ballparks were used when a new ballpark was planned for an expansion team or moving franchise, but was not completed.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] This occurred for a few reasons, such as delays or a desire to hold off until the deal is settled.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] In this case, an established building is used as a temporary home, often a minor league park.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] The first temporary ballparks were not actually used by expansion teams but by established franchises.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] When the Dodgers and Giants moved to California from New York, they played in Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum and Seals Stadium respectively while Dodger Stadium and Candlestick Park were being built.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Converted ballparks were an alternative to building an entirely new stadium.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] These parks were pre-existing minor league or college facility that were expanded to fit a major league team.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Converted ballparks are distinct from football stadia that were converted to multi-purpose parks in that converted ballparks were originally built for baseball only, albeit for a non-major league level.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Early converted ballparks were Memorial Stadium in Baltimore, Municipal Stadium in Kansas City, and Metropolitan Stadium in Bloomington, Minnesota.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] All three were expanded minor league facilities, although Baltimore and the Met were constructed with the idea of expanding to major league level in mind.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Kansas City was a true established minor league park that was substantially expanded to accommodate major league size crowds.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Temporary ballparks made a comeback in 2020, when Sahlen Field was used as a temporary MLB facility by the Toronto Blue Jays in the 2020 season and 2021 season due to Canada's travel restrictions following the outbreak of COVID-19, which prevented them from playing in the Rogers Centre.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Sutter Health Park is the temporary home of the Athletics from 2025 to 2027 leading up to the franchise's move to Las Vegas.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] After extensive damage to Tropicana Field by Hurricane Milton, it was announced that Steinbrenner Field will serve as the temporary home field for the Tampa Bay Rays during their 2025 season.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] These two types of ballpark are distinct because of their use, not their design.
[src:ballpark/ballpark-p03] Because of this, a temporary or converted ballpark can also be any of the other types: jewel box, modern, multi-purpose, etc.
